<p><ent>Lief</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lief
<hw>Lief</hw> <pr>(l⟦emac⟧f)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>lieve</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OE. <ets>leef</ets>, <ets>lef</ets>,
<ets>leof</ets>, AS. <ets>le⟦iacute⟧f</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>liof</ets>, OFries. <ets>liaf</ets>, D. <ets>lief</ets>, G.
<ets>lieb</ets>, OHG. <ets>liob</ets>, Icel. <ets>lj<?/fr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>ljuf</ets>, Goth. <ets>liubs</ets>, and E. <ets>love</ets>.
⟦root⟧124. See <er>Love</er>, and cf. <er>Believe</er>, <er>Leave</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Furlough</er>, <er>Libidinous</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Dear; beloved.</def> <mark>[Obs., except in
poetry.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧My <xex>liefe</xex> mother.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Chaucer.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧My <xex>liefest</xex> liege.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As thou art <qex>lief</qex> and dear.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <note>(Used with a form of the verb <xex>to be</xex>, and
the dative of the personal pronoun.)</note> <def>Pleasing; agreeable;
acceptable; preferable.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See
<er>Lief</er>, <pos>adv.</pos>, and <xex>Had as lief</xex>, under
<er>Had</er>.</see>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full <qex>lief</qex> me were this counsel for to hide.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death me <qex>liefer</qex> were than such despite.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Willing; disposed.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am not <qex>lief</qex> to gab.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He up arose, however <qex>lief</qex> or loth.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lief</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lief
<hw>Lief</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A dear one; a sweetheart.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lief</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lief
<hw>Lief</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Gladly; willingly; freely; -- now
used only in the phrases, <ecol><b>had as lief</b></ecol>, and
<ecol><b>would as lief</b></ecol>; <as>as, I had, or would, as
<ex>lief</ex> go as not</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All women <qex>liefest</qex> would⟦br⟧
Be sovereign of man's love.</q> <rj><qau>Gower.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had as <qex>lief</qex> the town crier spoke my lines.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far <qex>liefer</qex> by his dear hand had I die.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The comparative <xex>liefer</xex> with <xex>had or
would</xex>, and followed by the infinitive, either with or without the
sign <xex>to</xex>, signifies <xex>prefer</xex>, <xex>choose as
preferable</xex>, <xex>would</xex> or <xex>had rather</xex>. In the 16th
century <xex>rather</xex> was substituted for <xex>liefer</xex> in such
constructions in literary English, and has continued to be generally so
used. See <cref>Had as lief</cref>, <cref>Had rather</cref>, etc. ,
under <er>Had</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liefsome</ent>⟦br⟧
